{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8d35bfc9-427c-491e-ade9-9dfe6c132e49","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these places:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` crash reports:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open Console → *Crash Reports* in the sidebar to browse them with a GUI.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — These are disabled by default on macOS. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file typically lands in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **`lldb`** — You can analyze either artifact:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.12345 ./YourApp\n   # or just read the .ips file as JSON/text\n   ```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report is usually the easiest starting point — it includes the faulting thread, stack traces, and signal info without any prior setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b320494b-88a7-4952-ae70-1616d88cc328","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question - no tools needed.","outputTokens":340,"requestId":"640D:145B57:1474940:17F505A:69EC19CE"},"id":"133d5525-ee6d-42b3-b50c-ac28bd42e5e4","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:33:12.884Z","parentId":"3cfe5f68-17d5-4883-b470-65b7c3c0a450"}
